text: Curr Microbiol (2015) 71:458–464 DOI 10.1007/s00284-015-0868-9 The SARP Family Regulator Txn9 and Two-Component Response Regulator Txn11 are Key Activators for Trioxacarcin Biosynthesis in Streptomyces bottropensis Kui Yang1,2 Gong-Li Tang2 Received: 8 February 2015 / Accepted: 26 May 2015 / Published online: 16 July 2015 (cid:2) Springer Science+Business Media New York 2015 Abstract Trioxacarcin A is a polyoxygenated, structurally complex antibiotic produced by Streptomyces spp., which possesses high anti-bacterial, anti-malaria, and anti-tumor activities. The trioxacarcin biosynthetic pathway involves type II polyketide synthases (PKSs) with L-isoleucine as a unique starter unit, as well as many complex post-PKS tai- loring enzymes and resistance and regulatory proteins. In this work, two regulatory genes, txn9 coding for a Strepto- myces antibiotic regulatory protein family regulator and txn11 for a two-component response regulator, were revealed to be absolutely required for trioxacarcin produc- tion by individually inactivating all the six annotated regu- latory genes in the txn cluster. Complementation assay suggested that these two activators do not have a regulatory cascade relationship. Moreover, transcriptional analysis showed that they activate 15 of the 28 txn operons, indi- cating that a complicated regulatory network is involved in the trioxacarcin production. study may be useful for improving the production of the highly potent trioxacarcin A. Streptomyces bottropensis NRRL 12051 and Streptomyces sp. B8652 produce the natural product trioxacarcin (TXN) A (Fig. 1a), which is a polyoxygenated, structurally complex antibiotic that possesses high anti-bacterial, anti-malaria, and anti-tumor activities [20, 29, 30]. TXN A resembles the pluramycin family of natural products [13], and not only intercalates DNA but its epoxide moiety also binds cova- lently to the guanine N7. Subsequent DNA strand cleavage produces the natural product gutingimycin (Fig. 1b) [8, 21, 24]. Meanwhile, the related trioxacarcin B (TXN B, Fig. 1a) is less active for the lack of the epoxide moiety [20]. To develop potential chemotherapeutic agents, Myers and co-workers synthesized TXN A and related analogs by employing a convergent, component-based sequence for rapid construction of structurally diverse synthetic analogs that would be inaccessible by any other means [17, 28]. Recently, a novel Lewis acid-induced cascade rearrange- ment of an epoxyketone to form the polyoxygenated 2,7- dioxabicyclo[2.2.1]heptane core of the biosynthetic pre- cursor trioxacarcin DC-45-A2 was described by Nicolaou and co-workers [23]. On the other hand, the TXN A biosynthetic pathway has also been extensively studied by Tang’s group. 13C-labeled precursor feeding experiments demonstrated that the scaffold was biosynthesized from one molecule of L-isoleucine and nine molecules of acetate, in the type II which suggested a different starter unit polyketide biosynthesis [34]. Microbial natural product biosynthetic gene clusters usu- ally include regulatory genes, which are the main point of connection with a plethora of conserved regulatory systems that monitor physiology, developmental state, population density, and environment of the organism to determine the onset and production level of each natural product [16]. Since the TXN A biosynthetic pathway involves so many proteins, determining how the S. bottropensis strain coordinates expression of the txn genes will require signiﬁcant effort. In this study, we used gene inactivation, complementation, and reverse transcription PCR (RT-PCR) analysis to identify two key activators for TXN A biosynthesis, the Streptomyces antibiotic regulatory protein (SARP) Txn9 and the two- component response regulator Txn11. These two proteins are components of a complicated regulatory network, and knowledge of its mechanism will likely be harnessed to improve methods for TXN A production in the future. Bacterial Strains, Media, and Primers Bacterial strains, plasmids, and primers are listed in Table 1 and S1. Escherichia coli DH5a and BW25113/ pIJ790 were used for plasmid DNA construction and PCR- targeting, respectively [12]. E. coli S17-1 was used for E. coli-Streptomyces conjugation [14]. S. bottropensis was grown in TSB [14] or SYG media [34]. Antibiotics used (100 lg mL-1), chloramphenicol were (25 lg mL-1), apramycin (50 lg mL-1), nalidixic acid (25 lg mL-1), and thiostrepton (10-30 lg mL-1). Construction of Gene Inactivation Mutants and Complementation

All gene mutants were constructed using a standard PCR- targeting method [12], and the primers used for gene inactivation are listed in Table S1. The apramycin resis- tance gene cassette from the pIJ773 plasmid [12] was used for the selection. For inactivation of txn9, 10, 11, and 22, the cosmid cZM04-4 was used; for inactivation of txn34 and 48, the cosmid cZM05-09-2 was used by the PCR- targeting method [12]. The apramycin-resistant exconju- gants that were obtained were mainly single-crossover mutants, which were then grown in TSB media without apramycin for several generations to screen for apramycin- resistant double-crossover clones that were veriﬁed by PCR analysis. Generally, between two and four independent clones for each gene mutant were obtained for further fermentation analysis. The complementation experiments were performed using derivatives of the integrative plasmid pSET152 [14]. The key positive regulatory genes txn9 or txn11 under the control of the ermE* promoter [2] were inserted into a Table 1 Strains and plasmids used in this study thiostrepton resistance cassette containing pSET1521 [27], and the recombinant constructs were introduced into the txn9 or txn11 mutants. Thiostrepton-resistant clones were then selected for further fermentation analysis. Fermentation and HPLC Analysis of TXN A To assess TXN A production, wild-type S. bottropensis NRRL 12051 and its derivative strains were inoculated in 50 mL SYG media with HP20 macroporous resin, and grown for 5 days. Precipitates of the bacterial culture were obtained by centrifugation followed by acetone soaking, evaporation of the acetone, and dissolving the resulting pellet in 2 mL methanol. After ﬁltration, the fermentation products were analyzed by HPLC [34]. Total RNA Extraction and Reverse Transcription PCR

The wild-type S. bottropensis strain NRRL 12051 and the txn9 and txn11 inactivation mutant strains were grown under the same conditions as those used for fermentation. Two time points (3 and 4 days) were selected for sample collection. The sampled bacterial pellet was ﬁrst ground to a ﬁne powder in a liquid nitrogen environment. Total RNA was extracted using TRIzol reagent (Invitrogen), and DNA was removed by treatment with RNase-free DNase I (New England Biolabs). The cDNA products were diluted threefold and 1 lL was used for each PCR ampliﬁcation. Genes Encoding Regulatory Proteins in the txn Cluster

Gene inactivation experiments suggested that the triox- acarcin biosynthetic gene cluster (txn) included 56 genes, which is very large for type II PKS systems [34]. Bioin- formatic analyses using the Pfam [7] and CDD [18] data- bases revealed that there are six regulatory genes within the txn cluster. txn9 codes for a SARP family regulator, which belongs to pathway-speciﬁc activators found in many secondary metabolite biosynthetic gene clusters [16, 32]. txn10 codes for a two-component sensory kinase and txn11 encodes a LuxR-type two-component response regulator, both of which probably form a two-component signal transduction system that senses a variety of external signals and regulates TXN A production [3, 15, 33]. txn22 and txn48 each code for two copies of a winged helix DNA- binding domain that is present in a broad range of organ- isms, from bacteria to humans, and plays complex roles in DNA transcription regulation [5, 9–11]. txn34 encodes a DeoR family transcriptional regulator that generally acts as a repressor in sugar metabolism [6, 25]. To probe their effects on TXN A production, the six reg- ulatory genes were individually inactivated by a PCR-tar- geting method [12], and each gene mutant was veriﬁed txn9 by PCR ampliﬁcation (Fig. 2a). This result is consistent with the conserved transcriptional activation roles of other genes in this family [16, 32]. Compared with the S. bottropensis wild-type strain, the TXN A yield of the txn10 inactivation mutant (strain T10M) only partially decreased (Fig. 2bIII), while the txn11 mutant (strain T11M) produced no TXN A (Fig. 2bIV). Complementation of the T11M mutant with the native txn11 gene (pT11) fully restored TXN A pro- duction (Fig. 2cIII). Finally, cross-complementation experiments of the strains T09M and T11M were also performed, and the fermentation results showed that the cross-complementa- tion did not restore TXN A production (Fig. 2cIV, V), which indicated that these two genes likely do not have a regulatory cascade relationship. Considering the above gene inactivation and comple- mentation experiments, two key positive regulatory genes (txn9 and txn11) were identiﬁed as being absolutely nec- essary for TXN A biosynthesis. RT-PCR results suggested that 28 operons are present in the txn cluster (Fig. 3a, b). For each operon, one primer pair was used for differ- ential expression analysis, and the results showed that Txn9 and Txn11 positively control more than a half (15) of the 28 operons (Fig. 3c and Table S3). Speciﬁcally, Txn9 absolutely activates eight operons, including txn9, txn20- 21, txn23-24, txn31-32, txn35-36, txn37-38, txn39-41, and txn44, while Txn11 absolutely activates txn3-4, txn5, txn6- 8, txn20-21, txn23-24, txn31-32, txn35-36, txn37-38, and txn39-41. Unexpectedly, these two activators shared six operons, including txn20-21, txn23-24, txn31-32, txn35-36, txn37-38, and txn39-41. Four operons, txn25, txn26-30, txn42-43, and txn45-47, are obviously controlled by the two activators, and the two operons txn9 and txn44 are only clearly controlled by Txn11. here we identiﬁed two key activators Txn9 and Txn11, which are encoded within the txn cluster. A cross-comple- mentation assay demonstrated that the two activators do not have a regulatory cascade relationship, and this result is consistent with the RT-PCR analysis showing that they only share six of the 15 regulated operons. Txn9 belongs to the best characterized pathway-speciﬁc regulators, the SARP family proteins, which mainly act as activators [32]. Examples of SARP proteins include Streptomyces coelicolor ActII-ORF4 for biosynthesis of the type II polyketide acti- norhodin (ACT) [1] and Streptomyces peucetius DnrI for the type II polyketide daunorubicin production [26]. The prop- erties of these regulators are often harnessed for increasing the production of fermentation products [19], such as fred- ericamycin production from native and heterologous hosts [4]. The sensory kinase Txn10 likely transduces signals from the environment to the response regulator Txn11 for downstream transcriptional regulation of txn expression. The only partially decreased TXN A production in the txn10 inactivation mutant (strain T10M) (Fig. 2bIII) might indi- cate that an alternative two-component sensory kinase could phosphorylate the corresponding response regulator Txn11 [15]. Many global regulators belong to members of two- component systems. One of the ﬁrst pleiotropic regulators of secondary metabolism to be identiﬁed is the S. coelicolor two-component system AbsA1 (a sensor kinase) -AbsA2 (a response regulator), which are encoded within the calcium- dependent antibiotic (CDA) biosynthetic gene cluster [22]. Phosphorylated AbsA2 negatively regulates ACT, undecyl- prodigiosin (RED), and CDA production through interac- tions with pathway-speciﬁc regulatory gene promoters of actII-ORF4, redZ, and cdaR, respectively [22]. Recently, Jiang and co-workers [33] characterized a novel two-com- ponent system, the S. coelicolor DraK-R pair. They showed that DraK-R directly activates ACT but represses yellow- pigmented type

F4, redZ, and cdaR, respectively [22]. Recently, Jiang and co-workers [33] characterized a novel two-com- ponent system, the S. coelicolor DraK-R pair. They showed that DraK-R directly activates ACT but represses yellow- pigmented type I polyketide (yCPK) production through the pathway-speciﬁc activator genes actII-ORF4 and kasO, respectively, while its role in RED biosynthesis is inde- pendent of the pathway-speciﬁc activator genes redD/redZ [33].

Additionally, we are not sure whether txn5 and txn6 are included in a operon since the RT-PCR products (txn5-6) were present at a very low level, which is in contrast to that for the txn6-7 RT-PCR products under the same PCR conditions (Fig. 3b). One reason for this result may be read-through from the upstream operon. As such, there may be a promoter immediately upstream of txn5, although differential expression results showed that these genes are txn5 and txn6-7). regulated in a similar way (Fig. 3c, Similarly, there may also be promoters between txn12 and txn13, txn15 and txn16, and txn47 and txn48. These puta- tive promoters await conﬁrmation by further experiments, such as primer extension analysis. The TXN A production depends on the SARP family regulator Txn9 and response regulator Txn11 in a similar manner as that for the biosynthetic regulation of the red- pigmented tripyrrole antibiotic RED that is controlled by the SARP family regulator RedD and response regulator RedZ [31]. For RED production, RedZ also controls RedD expression [31], while in the TXN A biosynthesis system, Txn11 only activates Txn9 expression obviously (Fig. 3c and Table S3). Moreover, additional regulators are involved in the TXN A biosynthetic pathway, which indi- cates the existence of a far more complex regulatory net- work that will be the subject of further studies. However, the two key activators Txn9 and Txn11 that were identiﬁed in this work will likely be useful in metabolic engineering that may enhance production of the highly potent TXN A in the near future.
